newsitem.title: USA: KCBT wheat ends lower but earlier losses trimmed.
newsitem.headline: KCBT wheat ends lower but earlier losses trimmed.

text.p: KCBT hard red winter wheat futures ended lower but earlier losses were trimmed on a late rally tied to mill buying, traders said.
"We bounced off the midsession lows as it appeared there was a flurry of domestic flour business done," a trader said.
But traders also noted a bearish undertone tied to ideas U.S. wheat was overvalued relative to world wheat prices.

Tunisia bought 175,000 tonnes of soft wheat at $179.87 and 176.87 per tonne for October, November and December shipment at a tender Thursday. Traders noted the prices paid were below current U.S. futures prices.
Traders said the business was encouraging but noted export business overall remained sluggish.
"Rallies are built on export business, not routine domestic business," one trader noted, referring to the brief mill buying rally.
Prudential Securities was said to be a seller of the December on the day while Smoot Grain reportedly was a buyer, traders said.
Wheat ended 1/4 to four cents per bushel lower with September down four at $4.54.
